Exercise 2 (30 marks)

In this exercise you will create lists of U.S. politicians and officials since the 1950s. You will create these lists by scraping Wikipedia. You must manually create the datasets below by scraping Wikipedia. You cannot find the lists elsewhere.

If your answers indicate that you did not use good scraping etiquette (as discussed in lecture and seminar), you will lose a substantial number of marks for this problem. Do not repeatedly make requests to a Wikipedia webpage by repeatedly calling the read_html() function. For example, you should not repeatedly run a chunk with read_html() in it, as you will repeatedly make a request to the web server. You should organise your code chunks to prevent this kind of behaviour.

Part 1. Create dataset of all major presidential candidates since the 1952 election

From the Wikipedia page for every presidential election since 1952, extract the names and parties of the top two candidates. For example, here is the page for the 2020 election: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_United_States_presidential_election. You should automate the process of finding the URL for each election.

In the top right corner of each Wikipedia page there is a box showing the top performing candidates. For most elections, the Wikipedia page will only display the two top performing candidates (a Democrat and a Republican). But occasionally there will be a third candidate that receives substantial votes and that will be displayed on the Wikipedia page.

Using the info in this box on each election page, you should create a long tibble that has five columns: election_year, candidate_name, candidate_party, pop_vote, pop_vote_perc, ec_vote, winner. The first three columns are self-explanatory. The pop_vote column should contain the number of votes cast for the candidate, the pop_vote_perc column should contain the popular vote percentage (as listed on the Wikipedia page), and the ec_vote should contain the number of electoral votes cast for the candidate. The winner column should be a dichotomous variable (0 or 1) depending on whether that candidate was elected president. U.S. presidential elections happen on a state-by-state basis, which means that the candidate who receives the most electoral votes is elected president, even if that candidate receives fewer popular votes.

Using the arrange() function, sort this tibble by election year (ascending order), then popular vote (descending order). Save this tibble directly in the folder for this exercise, naming it pres_cands_df.csv.

After you have created the tibble, display/print only the rows corresponding to the 1992 election, the 2008 election and the 2016 election.

Part 2. Create dataset of all U.S. senators since January 1953

The national legislature of the U.S. is called the U.S. Congress and it is divided into two chambers: the U.S. Senate and the U.S. House of Representatives. Both chambers of the U.S. Congress operate on a two year basis, with each two-year period being referred to with a chronological number. For example, the current two-year term is the â118th Congressâ and it began January 3, 2023 and ends January 3, 2025.

In this part, you will create a tibble of all U.S. senators from January 1953 until now. You will do this by scraping each Wikipedia page containing the list of U.S. senators for each of the Congresses since 1952. You will start with the 83rd Congress (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_United_States_senators_in_the_83rd_Congress) and end with the 118th Congress (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_United_States_senators_in_the_118th_Congress). You should automate the process of creating each URL you will need to scrape.

You should create a tibble that has four columns: congress, senator_name, senator_state, senator_party. The first column will indicate which congress (e.g., the 118th, etc.) and the remaining columns will have information about each senator. Note that each states in the United States has two senators at a time. For example, since there there are currently 50 states in the United States (see a list here), there are currently 100 seats in the Senate. Of course, since senators occasionally die or resign, there are short periods of time where some Senate seats are vacant.

Using the arrange() function, sort this tibble by Congress number (descending order), then state (ascending order), then senator name (ascending order). Save this tibble directly in the folder for this exercise, naming it sens_df.csv.

After you have created the tibble, display/print only the rows showing the senators from California in the 90th and 115th Congresses.

Some hints:

  • Since 1953, the number of states (and thus the number of senators) has changed.
  • Starting with the 114th Congress, the table format changes on the Wikipedia pages.
  • There may also be other small changes in formatting that you need to deal with. However, please do not repeatedly scrape the same page, as this is bad etiquette!

Part 2. How many judges have multiple appointments?

In theory, an individual can receive several appointments to different judge positions during their lifetime. For example current Supreme Court Justice Sonia Sotomayor has had three appointments as judge on three different courts: U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York (from 1992 to 1998), the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit (from 1998 to 2009) and now the U.S. Supreme Court (from 2009 to now).

Create a long version of this dataset where each row corresponds to a specific appointment. After you have created the tibble, display/print only the first 5 rows of the tibble you created using the print() function adding the argument n=5.

Create another tibble that shows how many judge appointments each person in this dataset had, where you sort the tibble in descending order of the number of appointments. After you have created the tibble, display/print only the first 5 rows of the tibble you created using the print() function adding the argument n=5. Then calculate the mean number of appointments and the median number of appointments.

Part 3. How many federal judges have there been over time?

Create a high quality visualisation depicting the number of actively serving judges on 1st of January of every year from 1790 to 2024. Hint: each judgeâs appointment begins on their âCommission Dateâ and ends on their âTermination Dateâ.

Part 4. Exploring judgesâ previous careers

In the Professional Career column of the original judges.csv file, each judgeâs previous work experiences are listed separated by semi-colons.

Exercise 4 (30 marks)

U.S. federal judges are nominated by the U.S. president and then confirmed by a majority vote of the U.S. Senate. A nominee can only take office as a federal judge after the U.S. Senate confirms them, so if the Senate votes against confirmation, then the nominee will not become a federal judge. As part of the U.S. Senate confirmation process, hearings are usually held to investigate the background of the individuals who are nominated by the President. Transcripts of these hearings are published here: https://www.congress.gov/senate-hearing-transcripts/. Note: the Judiciary Committee of the U.S. Senate is responsible for holding hearings about the nomination of federal judges.

In this exercise, you will use Rselenium to find every hearing transcript corresponding to a federal judicial nomination during the 117th Congress. You should start at this page: https://www.congress.gov/senate-hearing-transcripts/ and then use Rselenium to click through the relevant places to find these hearing transcripts. Your Rselenium webscraper should mimic a human, meaning that it should go as slow as a human would go. More specifically: you should have at least a delay of 2 seconds between each action.

If your answers indicate that you did not use good scraping etiquette (as discussed in lecture and seminar), you will lose a substantial number of marks for this problem. Do not repeatedly make requests to a webpage by repeatedly using the navigate() function, or repetitively interact with elements in a way that is unnecessary. For example, you should not repeatedly run a chunk that reloads webpages or clicks links, as you will repeatedly be making requests to the web server. You should organise your code chunks to prevent this kind of behaviour.

Part 1. Launch the browser and find hearings from the 117th Congress
